texts.text: introducing on the NextGen bar exam. Counseling Integrated Question Sets require students to answer a series of six multiple choice or short answer questions focused on client counseling or dispute resolution, as they work through an unfolding common fact pattern that also contains rules or elicits rules students have memorized. 1

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Students who matriculated to law school in 2023 will need to answer Counseling Integrated Question Sets in order to obtain their law licenses in the at least seven states and territories that will administer the NextGen bar exam in July 2026. 2 Students who matriculated after 2023 will also need to answer Counseling Integrated Question Sets in order to obtain their law licenses in the numerous other states and territories that will begin rolling out the NextGen bar exam in July 2027 and thereafter. 3
texts.text: Students who matriculated to law school in 2023 will need to answer Counseling Integrated Question Sets in order to obtain their law licenses in the at least seven states and territories that will administer the NextGen bar exam in July 2026. 2 Students who matriculated after 2023 will also need to answer Counseling Integrated Question Sets in order to obtain their law licenses in the numerous other states and territories that will begin rolling out the NextGen bar exam in July 2027 and thereafter. 3

texts.label: text
texts.orig: To aid in this endeavor, faculty at Mitchell Hamline School of Law developed a five-step method and related tips for completing Counseling Integrated  Question  Sets  that  was  taught  to  358  students  at  Mitchell Hamline during their first semester of law school in 2024. The goal was to  test  the  method,  solicit  student  feedback,  and  make  responsive refinements.

The goal was to  test  the  method,  solicit  student  feedback,  and  make  responsive refinements.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: This article provides readers with the five-step method, an overview of student feedback, and the adjustments made to the method based on that feedback. Appendix A contains a student handout with the relevant method and tips. 4

texts.orig: A. Step One
texts.text: A. Step One

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The first step of the method is to read the call of the first question in the Counseling Integrated Question Set to get a high-level sense of the area of law being tested. If the call of the question does not give the reader a sense of the area of law being tested, the reader is instructed to scan the material preceding the question, which may consist of some facts and law, depending on the question.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The reason for this step is to equip the reader to efficiently analyze the preceding law and facts by enabling the reader to view those law and facts through their preexisting knowledge base on the area of law being tested. For example, if the area of law being tested is the tort of battery, the reader can begin thinking about how the elements and subrules for battery apply to the law and facts in the problem. Even if the reader does not have a preexisting knowledge base on the area of law being tested, knowing they lack such knowledge will beneficially cue the reader to pay special attention to any sources of law provided in the problem.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: B. Step Two
texts.text: B. Step Two

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The second step is to critically read the: (1) law and then the (2) facts above the first question, taking notes as one reads, and thinking about how the law and facts fit together. Readers are asked to read the law before the facts so they can quickly determine what facts are relevant in light of the law without having to read the facts multiple times. The reason readers are prompted to take notes as they read is to help the reader understand and remember what they read upon the first reading. Further,  readers  are  asked  to  think  about  how  the  law  and  facts  fit together  because  combining  law  and  facts  is  a  core  lawyering  skill expected to be required to answer many of the questions in Counseling Integrated Question Sets.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: C. Step Three
texts.text: C. Step Three

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The third step is to reread the call of the question. This step reminds the reader of the call of the question and creates a natural flow between the step of reading the question and developing an answer.
texts.text: The third step is to reread the call of the question. This step reminds the reader of the call of the question and creates a natural flow between the step of reading the question and developing an answer.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: D. Step Four
texts.text: D. Step Four

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The fourth step is to develop an answer to the first question in one's head if possible. The reason for this instruction is to provide the examinee with  dedicated  time  to  analyze  the  issue  and  answer  the  question  if possible.  If  the  question  is  a  multiple-choice  question,  occasionally examinees will  be  able  to  answer  the  question  without  looking  at  the answer choices, which are deliberately designed to deceive. Other times, examinees will need to move on to Step Five before developing an answer because they will need the information in the answer choices to do so.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: E. Step Five
texts.text: E. Step Five

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The fifth step differs based on whether the question type is multiple choice or short answer. If multiple choice, readers are asked to read the answer choices from top to bottom, crossing out or disregarding incorrect answers as they read, and selecting the best answer choice or choices, as instructed.  The  reason  for  this  step  is  that  examinees  often  need  the information  in  the  answer  choices  in  order  to  answer  the  question. Examinees  are  also  encouraged  to  work  through  the  question,  top  to bottom, crossing out or disregarding answers as they read to efficiently identify the correct answer choice(s) without skipping around and risking getting lost in the question. Examinees are further instructed to select the best answer choice or choices because, as noted below, the bar examiners may ask examinees to select multiple answer choices.
texts.text: The fifth step differs based on whether the question type is multiple choice or short answer. If multiple choice, readers are asked to read the answer choices from top to bottom, crossing out or disregarding incorrect answers as they read, and selecting the best answer choice or choices, as instructed.  The  reason  for  this  step  is  that  examinees  often  need  the information  in  the  answer  choices  in  order  to  answer  the  question. Examinees  are  also  encouraged  to  work  through  the  question,  top  to bottom, crossing out or disregarding answers as they read to efficiently identify the correct answer choice(s) without skipping around and risking getting lost in the question. Examinees are further instructed to select the best answer choice or choices because, as noted below, the bar examiners may ask examinees to select multiple answer choices.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: If short answer, readers are prompted to write sentences, phrases, or words, as instructed, that specifically answer the question. The reason for this step is that examinees can answer Counseling Integrated Question Set short answer questions using brief sentences, clauses, or words and need to avoid crafting lengthy answers in paragraph form, as discussed below.
texts.text: If short answer, readers are prompted to write sentences, phrases, or words, as instructed, that specifically answer the question. The reason for this step is that examinees can answer Counseling Integrated Question Set short answer questions using brief sentences, clauses, or words and need to avoid crafting lengthy answers in paragraph form, as discussed below.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: In conclusion, readers are then told to repeat steps one through five for  each  question  in  the  Counseling  Integrated  Question  Set,  skipping steps that do not apply, until they exhaust the questions.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: This article invites further testing of the method and tips for students in  their  final  semester  of  law  school  to  see  if  these  students  provide different  feedback  than  their  1L  counterparts  due  to  their  increased knowledge  and  experience. 21 This  article  also  invites  testing  of  the method and tips on further Counseling Integrated Question Sets released by the NCBE. texts.orig: V. M ETHODOLOGICAL R EFLECTIONS
texts.text: V. M ETHODOLOGICAL R EFLECTIONS

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The  process  used  in  this  study  of  developing  a  method  for performing a legal task such as Counseling Integrated Question Sets, and testing that method by soliciting student feedback, and making responsive refinements ('develop - solicit student feedback - refine') is well-suited to a range of methods taught by legal educators, including methods for critical reading, case briefing, outlining, and answering essay questions.
texts.text: The  process  used  in  this  study  of  developing  a  method  for performing a legal task such as Counseling Integrated Question Sets, and testing that method by soliciting student feedback, and making responsive refinements ('develop - solicit student feedback - refine') is well-suited to a range of methods taught by legal educators, including methods for critical reading, case briefing, outlining, and answering essay questions.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: This  process  is  valuable  because  students  are  well-equipped  to provide relevant and important feedback to legal educators. Students who are high enough academic performers to reach law school have, even if implicitly,  spent  years  using  different  methods  to  achieve  various educational objectives and presumably altering methods that yielded poor academic results.
texts.text: This  process  is  valuable  because  students  are  well-equipped  to provide relevant and important feedback to legal educators. Students who are high enough academic performers to reach law school have, even if implicitly,  spent  years  using  different  methods  to  achieve  various educational objectives and presumably altering methods that yielded poor academic results.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: That said, the utility of student feedback can be limited by an array of factors. For example, in this study, the students' perception of the method's efficacy may have been skewed by their lack of experience. The students in this study were in their first semester of law school and had  limited  experience  completing  legal  problems  like  Counseling Integrated Question Sets.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: On  balance,  however,  the  'develop  -  solicit  student  feedback  refine' process still provides legal educators with relevant and important information  and  has  at  least  three  distinct  benefits  over  assessing  a method's efficacy using students' performance scores. First, collecting and analyzing student feedback is often more feasible for legal educators than collecting and analyzing quantitative data like performance scores. This  is  particularly  true  when,  as  is  so  often  the  case,  analysis  of quantitative  data  requires  the  administration  of  sophisticated  statistical techniques such as regression analyses. Second, the process of collecting and analyzing student feedback over student performance scores has the advantage of yielding students' qualitative suggestions for improving any given method. Third, students themselves receive a unique benefit when asked to provide feedback on a method in the form of improving their metacognitive skills. 23 While collecting student feedback may be slightly more difficult than collecting performance scores, any added burden is modest due to the fact that many legal educators are well-equipped to solicit feedback from their students (captive survey participants) through technological tools such as Canvas and SurveyMonkey.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: Overview of Integrated Question Sets
texts.text: Overview of Integrated Question Sets

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Integrated Question Sets ('IQSs') are a type of question the NCBE is introducing on the NextGen bar exam. According to the NCBE, 'just under a quarter of the NextGen bar exam will be devoted to IQSs. Each of these sets is based on a common fact scenario and may include some legal resources (e.g., excerpts of statutes or judicial opinions) and/or supplemental documents (e.g., a police report or excerpt from a deposition) . . . In addition to testing doctrinal law, some IQSs will focus on counseling and/or dispute resolution [('Counseling IQSs')]; other sets will focus on drafting or editing a legal document [('Drafting IQSs')].' This handout addresses Counseling IQSs.
texts.text: Integrated Question Sets ('IQSs') are a type of question the NCBE is introducing on the NextGen bar exam. According to the NCBE, 'just under a quarter of the NextGen bar exam will be devoted to IQSs. Each of these sets is based on a common fact scenario and may include some legal resources (e.g., excerpts of statutes or judicial opinions) and/or supplemental documents (e.g., a police report or excerpt from a deposition) . . . In addition to testing doctrinal law, some IQSs will focus on counseling and/or dispute resolution [('Counseling IQSs')]; other sets will focus on drafting or editing a legal document [('Drafting IQSs')].' texts.orig: Tips for Completing Counseling Integrated Question Sets
texts.text: Tips for Completing Counseling Integrated Question Sets

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: (1) The Law
texts.text: (1) The Law

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: a. Counseling IQSs involve multiple (two or more) areas of law.
texts.text: Counseling IQSs involve multiple (two or more) areas of law.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: b. Sometimes the bar examiners will give you the law; sometimes you will have to use law you have memorized. If the bar examiners give you the law, that law trumps any law you have memorized.
texts.text: Sometimes the bar examiners will give you the law; sometimes you will have to use law you have memorized. If the bar examiners give you the law, that law trumps any law you have memorized.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: c. Integrate everything you have learned during law school as you think through the question, including about the United States legal system, litigation process, and hierarchy of legal authorities.
texts.text: Integrate everything you have learned during law school as you think through the question, including about the United States legal system, litigation process, and hierarchy of legal authorities.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: (2) Short Answer Questions
texts.text: (2) Short Answer Questions

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: a. You do not need to IRAC your answer or use the 'Legal Conclusion because Facts, so explanation if needed' sentence structure.
texts.text: You do not need to IRAC your answer or use the 'Legal Conclusion because Facts, so explanation if needed' sentence structure.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: b. Each short answer question will give you the suggested length (e.g., number of sentences), format (e.g., sentences, phrases, or words), and the number of answer fields in which you should provide your answers (e.g., a question asking for three facts will contain three answer fields).
texts.text: Each short answer question will give you the suggested length (e.g., number of sentences), format (e.g., sentences, phrases, or words), and the number of answer fields in which you should provide your answers (e.g., a question asking for three facts will contain three answer fields).

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: c. Be aware that there can be multiple 'correct' answers.
texts.text: Be aware that there can be multiple 'correct' answers.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: d. Your answers should be as specific as possible.
texts.text: Your answers should be as specific as possible.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: i. For example, you want to say:
texts.text: For example, you want to say:

texts.text: Be precise with your language; be careful not to misstate the law or the facts.

texts.label: list_item

texts.text: You do not need to provide citations.

texts.orig: (3) Multiple-Choice Questions
texts.text: (3) Multiple-Choice Questions

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: a. The bar examiners may ask you to select multiple answer choices (i.e., one, two); be careful to select the number requested.
texts.text: The bar examiners may ask you to select multiple answer choices (i.e., one, two); be careful to select the number requested.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: (4) What to Do if You Don't Know What to Do
texts.text: (4) What to Do if You Don't Know What to Do

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: a. If you get stuck on a question, make an educated guess and move on (do not dwell).
texts.text: If you get stuck on a question, make an educated guess and move on (do not dwell).

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: b. Partial credit is available for questions; do not skip a question just because you do not know the full answer.
texts.text: Partial credit is available for questions; do not skip a question just because you do not know the full answer.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: (5) Beware of Going Backwards
texts.text: (5) Beware of Going Backwards

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: a. While information provided earlier in the set may be used to answer questions later in the set, information provided later in the set should never be used to answer questions earlier in the set.
texts.text: While information provided earlier in the set may be used to answer questions later in the set, information provided later in the set should never be used to answer questions earlier in the set.

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: b. If you have extra time and check your earlier answers, be careful not to talk yourself out of a correct answer.
texts.text: If you have extra time and check your earlier answers, be careful not to talk yourself out of a correct answer.
